00:00:01.770 --> 00:00:03.230
&gt;&gt;presenter: Thanks everyone for coming today.

00:00:03.230 --> 00:00:08.870
We have author George Dyson here to talk about
his upcoming book, or brand new book Turingís

00:00:08.870 --> 00:00:12.590
Cathedral: The Origins of the Digital Universe.

00:00:12.590 --> 00:00:17.860
The creation stories of revolutionary technologies
is pretty deeply embedded in American culture.

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:22.400
We all learned very young about Benjamin Franklinís
experiments with electricity and Thomas Edison

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:26.550
work on the light bulb, however, the story
of the invention of the computer, which is

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:31.050
arguably going to have much, a far greater
impact even though itís based functionally

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:35.250
on those earlier technologies, is largely
missing from our collective knowledge.

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:41.250
Dysonís new work sheds important light on
this and, on this creation of this and, uh,

00:00:41.250 --> 00:00:45.430
this wonderful invention and how the digital
universe exploded in the aftermath of World

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:46.540
War II.

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:51.490
So, besides going deep into the early history
of the computer Turingís Cathedral also offers

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:56.000
a series of provocative suggestions as to
where the digital universe may be headed next.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.559
And so without further ado, letís welcome
George Dyson.

00:00:58.559 --> 00:00:59.559
[Applause]

00:00:59.559 --> 00:01:01.460
&gt;&gt;George Dyson: Thank you.

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:06.670
Itís great to be here and see everybody working.

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:12.560
I come here every summer for Sci-Fu but in
the old days of Sci-Fu, sort of, we mingled

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:16.749
with the Google people that was part of the
idea but now Sci-Fu sort of isolated and we

00:01:16.749 --> 00:01:21.310
donít really see the people who are working,
weíre separated from the Sci-Fu people.

00:01:21.310 --> 00:01:25.959
But I was here seven years ago, in fact, thatís
where the title of this book comes from and

00:01:25.959 --> 00:01:30.130
Iíll explain that a little later.

00:01:30.130 --> 00:01:37.189
And, Iím coming to this; I just have to say
this in all honesty, from totally left field.

00:01:37.189 --> 00:01:43.539
Iím not a computer scientist, Iím not, I
dropped out of high school at age sixteen

