a two dimensional speed of light address matrix

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:16.060
which is the world that you guys are all living
in today, where you can give a numerical coordinate

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:17.690
and get back a string of bits.

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:21.329
That was the thing that was new and thatís
what Von Neumann saw.

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:26.169
The model was Turing, Alan Turing's one dimensional
model and Von Neumann made it two dimensional,

00:04:26.169 --> 00:04:29.860
thatís sort of the key moment in history
Iím trying to look at.

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:36.099
Not who invented the first computer, weíre
gonna argue about that forever.

00:04:36.099 --> 00:04:39.419
You know, weíll learn by arguing about it,
but it sort of gets pointless after a while.

00:04:39.419 --> 00:04:46.240
So in 1984 just after I came down from the
tree house, I wrote this piece about Von Neumann

00:04:46.240 --> 00:04:49.849
trying to give it to the people at my sisterís
conference, who really were not interested.

00:04:49.849 --> 00:04:56.330
They were interested in whether DOS, which
sort of flavor of DOS would win next year.

00:04:56.330 --> 00:04:57.650
So nothing happened.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:04.080
