00:08:01.309 --> 00:08:07.210
And Von Neumann when he built this machine,
he needed to write the code for it, there

00:08:07.210 --> 00:08:10.569
was nobody who did that kind of thing, so
he taught Klara how to write the codes.

00:08:10.569 --> 00:08:14.310
So she wrote all the early codes and these
letters were all back and forth.

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:17.680
Heís, like there heís at Los Alamos, sheís
in Washington D.C.

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:23.110
And there sheís at Aberdeen where the ENIAC
was, so sheís writing codes for the ENIAC

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:29.550
and heís, uh, at Oak Ridge laboratory, nuclear
laboratory in Tennessee.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:36.020
So all this stuff was there, half in Hungarian,
but Bela Bolobas and his wife Gabriella translated

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:39.330
it for me, so that, thatís the source of
this book.

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:43.950
When, until then I was struggling, then I
had the raw material to really bring this

00:08:43.950 --> 00:08:44.950
story to life.

00:08:44.950 --> 00:08:49.700
And Klara was a fantastic writer, even though
